  "opinion": "As a mechanic who's spent years fixing cars and machines, I've seen how stereotypes can quietly undermine people's confidence. Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's the feeling that if you're a woman or person of color in a tech field, you might 'fail' because of who you are, not what you know. When I work with kids in my shop, I've noticed how some girls hesitate to ask questions about engines because they think they 'don't belong' in this space. That's stereotype threat in action. It's real, and it's harmful. We absolutely must address it—not with big speeches, but by creating environments where everyone feels safe to learn without fear of judgment. In my shop, I've started by welcoming students from all backgrounds, making sure they know their questions are valid and their presence matters. When someone feels seen and supported, they perform better. I've also noticed how important it is to celebrate diverse stories in STEM—like how my own immigrant parents taught me to think critically about problems, even when they didn't have formal education. By focusing on individual strengths rather than group labels, we can build a more inclusive culture. Addressing stereotype threat isn't about changing people—it's about changing how we see each other. And that's something we can all do, starting with the small acts of patience and encouragement.",
